summary: My grandmother used to say drifloon would take children away because they would often confuse them for lost spirits. She says...
question: My grandmother used to say drifloon would take children away because they would often confuse them for lost spirits. She says child spirits were common to drifloon and would often use them as guides to the other side. Thus the drifloons often confused both of them and would accidently take a child who was still alive. And since spirits aren't heavy it's easy for them to carry, but children who are not spirits are a bit heavier thus when they try to carry them they accidentally drop the children.
answer:
Very interesting…

It would certainly make sense for why they’re also known as ‘Signposts for Wandering Spirits’.

body:
I want my fucking Spiritomb

I just walked three miles to hit 6 more Pokestops I haven’t been to before. No stopping. Yesterday I walked to work, pulled an eight hour shift of standing, and walked home. And now less than 24 hours later I just get up and decide, “hey, time to walk almost to the other end of town, around the entire downtown area, and back home.”

Also Miles the Feebas is now Miles the Milotic!

caption:
Pokemon Anything Month - Week 4: Joestar Parts 1-6 Halloween **If you want me to fully color these characters in a complete art, then leave a comment near the end of October**
In light of Jojo’s Bizarre Adventure: Golden Wind, being out. I wanted to make this one about all the Joestar Pokemon I did and swap their costumes for Halloween. Ihad a few other things in my family to work on, so that’s partly why this was delayed.

Part 1: Jonathan Joestar + Luxray: Swap with Giorno
Part 2: Joesph Joestar + Feraligatr: Swap with Jolyne
Part 3: Jotaro Kujo + Pangoro: Swap with Jonathan
Part 4: Josuke Higashikata +Furfrou: Swap with Joseph
Part 5: Giorno Giovanna + Ninetales: Swap with Jotaro
Part 6: Jolyne Cujoh + Braixen: Swap with Josuke
